# Project Architecture Rules

## Core Stack

- Use Slim Framework 4 as lightweight routing backbone.
- Use PHP 8.2+ procedural modern style.
- Use PDO with raw SQL for database operations.
- Database is always MariaDB.
- Use Bootstrap 5 for frontend UI.
- Use jQuery 3 for DOM interaction and AJAX.
- Use Font Awesome 7 for icons.
- Use ApexCharts for charts and analytics visualization.
- Use nginx + php-fpm deployment style.

---

# UI / UX Design Philosophy

- Create a modern SaaS-style web app UI using Bootstrap 5.
- Apply a clean and minimalist design.
- Prefer generous whitespace and comfortable spacing.
- Prefer subtle border radius using:
  rounded-3
- Prefer clean card components.
- Prefer soft shadows over heavy shadows.
- Prefer subtle borders over excessive gradients.
- Avoid overly colorful UI unless explicitly requested.
- Use Google Font:
  Inter
  as the default global typeface.
- Implement Dark Mode / Light Mode toggle using Bootstrap native color modes:
  data-bs-theme="dark"
- Default theme should be:
  light mode
- Keep layouts professional, efficient, and mobile responsive.
- Authentication forms should remain mobile friendly and simple.
- Backend sidebar should be collapsible on mobile devices.
- Prefer Bootstrap utility classes over excessive custom CSS.
- Avoid excessive custom CSS when Bootstrap utility classes are sufficient.

---

# Standard Frontend Libraries

These frontend libraries are considered standard UI libraries and should be preferred over alternative plugins.

Avoid duplicate frontend libraries with overlapping functionality.

Use stable production versions only.
Avoid alpha, beta, or experimental versions.

Prefer CDN assets from:
- https://cdn.jsdelivr.net

Avoid mixing multiple CDN providers unless explicitly required.

Maintain proper frontend asset loading order:
- jQuery first
- Bootstrap bundle second
- Plugin libraries after Bootstrap

---

## Alert & Confirm
Use:
- SweetAlert2

Always replace native:
- alert()
- confirm()

---

## Table
Use:
- DataTables Core
- DataTables Bootstrap 5
- DataTables Buttons

Requirements:
- Use Bootstrap 5 integration
- Include Indonesian locale (id.json)
- Use Excel export button only

---

## Select Box
Use:
- Select2

Use for:
- searchable dropdown
- large select options
- AJAX selectbox

---

## Date & Time Picker
Use:
- Flatpickr

Use for:
- datepicker
- datetime picker
- time picker

---

## WYSIWYG Editor
Use:
- Summernote

Use for:
- rich text editor
- article editor
- content management

---

## Loading Indicator
Use:
- LoadingOverlay

Use loading overlay:
- during AJAX request
- during page navigation within same hostname
- except links using target="_blank"

---

## Input Masking
Use:
- Inputmask

Use when:
- phone number
- currency
- date formatting
- formatted input

---

## Form Validation
Use:
- Parsley.js

Use for:
- client-side form validation

---

## Password Strength Meter
Use:
- pwstrength-bootstrap

Use for:
- change password form
- reset password form
- registration form

---

## Panorama Viewer
Use:
- Pannellum

Use only when:
- 360 panorama viewer is needed

---

## PDF Viewer
Use:
- Mozilla PDF.js

Use for:
- browser PDF preview
- embedded PDF viewing
- in-browser PDF reader

Avoid forcing PDF download when browser preview is more appropriate.

---

# Architecture Philosophy

- Keep architecture simple, lightweight, fast, and maintainable.
- Avoid enterprise patterns and over-engineering.
- Avoid heavy MVC separation.
- Prefer minimal file count for one feature.
- One file may contain PHP logic, SQL query, HTML view, modal, and AJAX handler when practical.
- Keep logic close to the view when it improves readability.
- Use JSON API only when necessary (AJAX, realtime data, async request).
- Prioritize simplicity and debugging ease.

# Architecture Philosophy

---

# View Rendering Rules

- Do not use template engines.
- Do not use:
  - Twig
  - Blade
  - Smarty
  - Latte
  - Mustache
  - Plates
  - or similar template systems
- Use traditional native PHP view rendering.
- HTML and PHP may coexist inside the same feature file when practical.
- Prefer direct PHP rendering using:
  require
  include
- Prefer lightweight server-rendered HTML output.
- Avoid unnecessary view abstraction layers.

---

# CRUD File Structure Philosophy

- Prefer combining create and update form into one:
  [modul]-post.php

- Use the same form file for:
  - create
  - edit/update

- Differentiate create/update mode using:
  - id parameter
  - mode parameter
  - existing database data

- Prefer keeping:
  [modul].php
  as the main feature page.

Examples:
- pengguna.php
- pengguna-post.php

- Main module file should commonly handle:
  - listing
  - datatable
  - filtering
  - delete process
  - lightweight detail actions

- Avoid excessive CRUD file splitting unless explicitly required.

---

# Modal Philosophy

- Prefer inline modal implementation inside the main feature file.
- Modal form and AJAX submit logic may remain inside the same feature file when practical.
- Avoid unnecessary modal file separation.
- Separate modal into:
  [modul]-modal.php
  only when modal complexity becomes too large or reusable.
- Avoid creating dedicated modal folders.

---

# Dependency Philosophy

- Use minimal dependencies.
- Avoid unnecessary Composer packages.
- Never use ORM (Eloquent, Doctrine, etc).
- Prefer raw SQL queries with PDO.
- Avoid Laravel-style abstractions.
- Avoid heavy service containers.
- Avoid repository pattern unless absolutely necessary.
- Avoid npm-based frontend build systems unless explicitly requested.
- Prefer CDN-based frontend libraries.
- Avoid heavy queue systems unless explicitly required.

---

# Middleware Rules

- Keep middleware usage minimal.
- Use middleware only when truly necessary.
- Avoid enterprise-style middleware architecture.
- Prefer simple procedural helper functions for:
  - authentication
  - authorization
  - validation
- Avoid excessive middleware layers.
- Keep application flow easy to trace and debug.

---

# Standard Backend Libraries

These libraries are considered pre-installed starter libraries and should be used whenever relevant functionality is needed.

Prefer these libraries instead of introducing alternative packages.

